om/2013/12/17/sunday-cable-ratings-the-real-housewives-of-atlanta-tops-night-homeland-bar-rescue-psych-more/222892/|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=December 17, 2013|date=December 17, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Brody leaves Akbari's body in his office, grabs his gun, and walks from the building, where he meets up with Carrie to go to a safe house. Lockhart reveals the location of the safe house to the Iranians, and Brody is arrested and summarily put on trial.  Brody is sentenced to public hanging, and insists Carrie is not there for the event (she goes anyway). Carrie finds out she has been promoted to station chief in Istanbul. Saul is fired after Lockhart takes control of the CIA.\n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n== Production==\nOn October 22, 2012, ''Homeland'' was renewed for a third season, consisting of 12 episodes,<ref name=\"S3\">{{cite web|title=Showtime\u00ae Orders Season Three of Homeland|url=http://www.cbspressexpress.com/showtime/releases/view?id=33365|publisher=[[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]|date=October 22, 2012|accessdate=December 15, 2012}}</ref> which premiered on September 29, 2013.<ref name=\"s3 premiere\">{{cite web |title=Showtime Moves 'Dexter' to Summer, Sets Premieres for New Dramas |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/showtimes-dexter-summer-homeland-premiere-411745 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Philiana |last=Ng |date=January 12, 2013 |accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nProduction for the third season began in late May 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2013/05/28/4068641/homeland-brings-claire-danes-to.html|title=Homeland shoots third season in uptown|first=Th\u00e9oden|last=Janes|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|date=May 28, 2013|accessdate=May 30, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215161307/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2013/05/28/4068641/homeland-brings-claire-danes-to.html|archive-date=December 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> continuing in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Homeland' to film in Raleigh|url=http://www.wral.com/-homeland-to-film-in-raleigh/12493017/|work=[[WRAL-TV|WRAL]]|publisher=[[Capitol Broadcasting Company]]|date=May 29, 2013 |accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> The series also filmed in [[Old San Juan, Puerto Rico]], which stood in for [[Caracas, Venezuela]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Puerto Rico Makes Debut on \"Homeland\"|url=http://www.caribjournal.com/2013/09/29/puerto-rico-makes-debut-on-homeland/|work=Caribbean Journal|date=September 29, 2013|accessdate=December 15, 2013}}</ref> The series was also planning on returning to Israel for additional filming, but filming moved to Morocco, due to ongoing conflicts in [[Syrian Civil War|Syria]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Homeland' Moves Israel Shoot to Morocco Amid Syria Debate|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-moves-israel-shoot-morocco-630796|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Michael|last=O'Connell|date=September 17, 2013|accessdate=December 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe third season has three previous guest actors\u2013[[Rupert Friend]], [[F. Murray Abraham]] and [[Sarita Choudhury]]\u2013promoted to series regulars.<ref name=Press>{{cite web|last=Bibel|first=Sara|title=Showtime Releases Premiere Dates for Original Series Including \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019, \u2018Homeland\u2019 & \u2018Ray Donovan\u2019|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/04/30/showtime-releases-premiere-dates-for-original-series-including-masters-of-sex-homeland-ray-donovan/180380/|work=TV by the Numbers|date=April 30, 2013|accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref><ref name=New>{{cite web|last=Sepinwall|first=Alan|title=Exclusive: 'Homeland' adds F. Murray Abraham and Sarita Choudhury as regulars|url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/exclusive-homeland-adds-f-murray-abraham-and-sarita-choudhury-as-regulars|work=Hitfix|date=May 9, 2013|accessdate=May 9, 2013}}</ref> [[Tracy Letts]] joined the cast playing Senator Andrew Lockhart, Chairman of Senate Select Committee on Intelligence, as a series regular.<ref name=New1>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Tracy Letts Upped To Regular On Showtime\u2019s \u2018Homeland\u2019|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/05/tracy-letts-upped-to-regular-on-showtimes-homeland/|work=Deadline|date=May 29, 2013|accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> [[Diego Klattenhoff]] and [[David Marciano]], who portray Mike Faber and Virgil, do not return as series regulars, but return in a recurring capacity.<ref name = Virgil/><ref>{{cite web|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|title=''Homeland'' Exclusive: Diego Klattenhoff Not Returning as a Series Regular In Season 3|url=http://tvline.com/2013/01/18/homeland-season-3-spoilers-diego-klattenhoff-leaving-mike/|work=TVLine|date=January 18, 2013|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> \n\n[[Barbara Hall (TV producer)|Barbara Hall]] joined as co-executive producer, after [[Meredith Stiehm]] left.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Rose, Lacey |author2=Belloni, Matthew |title='Homeland' Adds 'Judging Amy's' Barbara Hall as Co-Executive Producer (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-judging-amys-barbara-hall-422808|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 20, 2013|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> [[James Yoshimura]] also joined as a writer and consulting producer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rose|first=Lacey|title='Homeland' Adds First New Writer For Season 3 (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-adds-first-new-writer-420749|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 12, 2013|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> Writer [[Henry Bromell]], who died on March 18, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|title=Henry Bromell, 'Homeland' executive producer, dies at 65|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-homeland-executive-producer-henry-bromell-dies-20130319,0,7832899.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Greg|last=Braxton|date=March 19, 2013|accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> is credited as executive producer for the whole season.<ref name=Bromell>{{cite web|last=Malcolm|first=Shawna|title=Henry Bromell\u2019s Legacy Looms Large Over \u2018Homeland\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/news/henry-bromells-legacy-looms-large-over-homeland-1200502856/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 28, 2013|accessdate=June 30, 2013}}</ref> [[Lesli Linka Glatter]], who directed the season 2 episode \"[[Q&A (Homeland)|Q&A]]\", and former ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'' co-executive producer and writer Patrick Harbinson both joined as co-executive producer.<ref name=Production>{{cite web|last=Saylor|first=Morgan|title=Juicy @showtime|url=http://instagram.com/p/ab13Wmjq3_/|publisher=[[Instagram]]|date=June 12, 2013|accessdate=June 14, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611142306/https://instagram.com/p/ab13Wmjq3_/|archivedate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> Michael Klick, who was credited as producer in the first two seasons, was promoted to co-executive producer.<ref name=Production/> Claire Danes became a producer beginning with the third season. Former series writer [[Meredith Stiehm]] rejoined the writing staff near the end of the third season, including co-writing the season finale, after departing ''Homeland'' to write for her new TV series ''[[The Bridge (2013 TV series)|The Bridge]]''.<ref name=Stiehm/> Stiehm will continue with the series through the fourth season and potential fifth season as well.<ref name=Stiehm>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/showrunner-shakeup-bridge-showrunner-meredith-657077|title=Showrunner Shakeup: 'The Bridge's' Meredith Stiehm Departs for 'Homeland'|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Rose|first=Lacey|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Ratings===\nIn its third season, ''Homeland'' became the first series on Showtime to surpass seven million total viewers weekly.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|title='Homeland' Third Season Finale Draws Record 2.4 Million Viewers|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/12/16/homeland-third-season-finale-draws-record-2-4-million-viewers/222824/|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=December 19, 2013|date=December 16, 2013}}</ref> The season finale, \"[[The Star (Homeland)|The Star]]\", was the highest rated episode of the series to date, with 2.38 million viewers for the original broadcast.<ref name=\"RatingE12\" />\n\n===Critical response===\nThe third season received mixed reviews from critics, with many of the criticisms targeted at the second half.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dietz|first1=Jason|title=TV Critics Are Getting Fed Up With Homeland. Are You Still On Board?|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/homeland-season-3-reviews-game-on|publisher=Metacritic|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref> The first two episodes received a [[Metacritic]] score of 77 out of 100, based on 23 reviews,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-3 |title=Homeland : Season 3 |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> but reviews became more mixed as the season progressed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan|first=Maureen|title=\u2018Homeland\u2019 Review: What The Heck Is Going On With This Show?|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/homeland-review_b_4125281.html|work=The Huffington Post|date=October 20, 2013|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=TV Critics Are Getting Fed Up With Homeland. Are You Still On Board?|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/homeland-season-3-reviews-game-on|publisher=Metacritic|first=Jason|last=Dietz|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTim Goodman of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''  wrote that the first two episodes of the season restored his faith in the series, with the emphasis on Carrie and Saul, and that \"the writing and acting in the first two episodes are exceptional.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/homeland-season-3-tv-review-635659 |title='Homeland' Season 3: TV Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Tim |last=Goodman |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> Robert Rorke of ''[[Newsday]]'' wrote that \"the third-season premiere ''Homeland'' delivers a strong episode that repairs much of the damage done last season to this excellent show\" and \"In balancing action with character development, ''Homeland'' offers something for everyone. The performances, as usual, are excellent.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2013/09/27/homeland-repairing-damage-done-by-last-season/ |title=\u2018Homeland\u2019 repairing damage done by last season |work=Newsday |first=Robert |last=Rorke |date=September 27, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> Robert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' praised the focus on the aftermath of the CIA bombing, and wrote \"The result of that change of focus is a return that's quieter than the tone ''Homeland'' set when it left us but just as intense, and\u2014when Danes is on screen\u2014just as emotionally wrenching.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/09/26/betrayal-homeland-combo-review/2876823/ |title='Homeland' is worth a visit; 'Betrayal' is best avoided |work=USA Today |first=Robert |last=Bianco |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> Matthew Wolfson of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' wrote \"Showing us the long-term impact of the attack on the lives of these characters, whose deep-seated motivations and fears have gradually been revealed to us over the last two seasons, allows ''Homeland'' to transcend its tendencies toward the hyperbolic and gives us a reason to suspend our disbelief.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/tv/review/homeland-season-three |title= Homeland: Season Three |work=Slate |first=Matthew |last=Wolfson |date=September 24, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> \n\nHowever, some critics had negative reviews for the season. Morven Crumlish of ''[[The Guardian]]'' found it tedious: \"A half-absorbed piece of fiction will leave the characters floundering in their mid-arc torpor. With no end in sight, though, Carrie and Brody can flounder without me.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Crumlish|first=Morven|title=Homeland has no end in sight, and I'm throwing in my cards|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/28/homeland-end-series-three|work=The Guardian|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> Gerard O'Donovan of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' agreed: \"The ludicrous plot contortions of this season\u2019s early episodes... had all been such a mess.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Donovan|first=Gerard|title=Homeland, series three, episode seven, Channel 4, review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10452658/Homeland-series-three-episode-seven-Channel-4-review.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=November 17, 2013|accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nThe season was nominated for Best Drama Series for the 2014 [[Writers Guild of America Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/05/writers-guild-award-nominations-2014-list-wga/ |title=''Breaking Bad'', ''Orange Is the New Black'', ''House of Cards'' Lead 2014 WGA Nominations |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=December 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> For the [[20th Screen Actors Guild Awards]], the cast was nominated for Best Drama Ensemble, [[Claire Danes]] was nominated for Best Drama Actress, and the series was nominated for Best Stunt Team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/11/sag-nominations-2014-list-screen-actors-guild/ |title=SAG Award Nominations: ''Breaking Bad'', ''Big Bang'', ''30 Rock'' Lead the Pack, Kerry Washington, Mayim Bialik Sneak In; ''Orange'', ''Mad Men'' Shut Out |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=December 11, 2013 |accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref> For the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]], Claire Danes was nominated for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series and [[Mandy Patinkin]] was nominated for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/emmy-nominations-2014-list-emmys-nominees-1201260236/ |title=2014 Emmy Awards: \u2018Game of Thrones,\u2019 \u2018Fargo\u2019 Lead Nominations |work=Variety |first=Brian |last=Lowry |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Home media release==\n''Homeland: The Complete Third Season'' was released as a widescreen region 1 four-disc DVD and three-disc Blu-ray box set in the United States and Canada on September 9, 2014.<ref name=\"region1a\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Homeland-Season-3-Press-Release/19996 |title=Homeland - Official Fox Press Release for 'The Complete 3rd Season' on DVD, Blu |publisher=TVShowsonDVD.com |first=David |last=Lambert |date=July 1, 2014 |accessdate=July 2, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714140148/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Homeland-Season-3-Press-Release/19996 |archivedate=July 14, 2014 }}</ref> In addition to the 12 episodes, it includes deleted scenes, audio commentary for \"The Star\" and two featurettes\u2014\"The Tower of David: Filming in Puerto Rico 3\" and \"The Last Days: Filming the Season Finale\".<ref name=\"region1a\"/> The same set was also released on September 8, 2014, in region 2<ref name=\"region2b\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B00DHB3SIK/ |title=Homeland - Season 3 [Blu-ray] |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> and on September 24, 2014, in region 4.<ref name=\"region4b\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ezydvd.com.au/blu-ray/homeland-season-3/dp/6151877|title=Homeland: Season 3|publisher=EzyDVD|accessdate=May 15, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517153033/http://www.ezydvd.com.au/blu-ray/homeland-season-3/dp/6151877|archivedate=May 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe season is also available for streaming online via [[Hulu]], as of August 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/movies/homeland-streaming-hulu/ |title=Now streaming: Showtime\u2019s hit political thriller \u2018Homeland\u2019 lands on Hulu |publisher=Digital Trends |first=Stephanie Topacio |last=Long |date=August 1, 2016 |accessdate=January 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.sho.com/homeland}}\n* {{IMDb episodes|1796960|Homeland}}\n* {{tv.com episodes|homeland-2011|80132|Homeland}}\n\n{{Homeland episodes}}\n\n[[Category:Homeland (TV series)|Season 3]]\n[[Category:2013 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Iran]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Season American political thriller television series Homeland}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = 3\n| bgcolour             = #FFC50A\n| image                = Homeland S3 DVD.jpg\n| image_upright        = 1.15\n| caption              = DVD cover art\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Claire Danes]] \n* [[Damian Lewis]]\n* [[Rupert Friend]]\n* [[Morena Baccarin]] \n* [[Jackson Pace]]\n* [[Morgan Saylor]]\n* [[Sarita Choudhury]]\n* [[Tracy Letts]]\n* [[F. Murray Abraham]]\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]]\n}}\n| country              = United States\n| num_episodes         = 12\n| network              = [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]\n| first_aired  = {{Start date|2013|9|29}}\n| last_aired   = {{End date|2013|12|15}}\n| episode_list         = List of Homeland episodes\n}}\n\nThe third season of the American television drama series ''[[Homeland (TV series)|Homeland]]'' premiered on September 29, 2013 on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]], and concluded on December 15, 2013, consisting of 12 episodes. The series is loosely based on the [[Israel]]i television series ''[[Prisoners of War (TV series)|Hatufim]]'' (English: ''Prisoners of War'') created by [[Gideon Raff]] and is developed for American television by [[Howard Gordon]] and [[Alex Gansa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tv.nytimes.com/show/5111863/Homeland/overview|title=Homeland \u2013 Listings |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{Main|List of Homeland characters}}\n\n===Main===\n{{multiple image\n| align  = right\n| footer = [[Claire Danes]], [[Damian Lewis]] and [[Mandy Patinkin]] (left to right) portray lead roles [[Carrie Mathison]], [[Nicholas Brody]] and Saul Berenson, respectively.\n| image1 = Claire Danes.jpg\n| width1 = 183\n| image2 = Damian Lewis Berlin 2015.jpg\n| width2 = 135\n| image3 = MandyPatinkin.jpg\n| width3 = 143\n}}\n{{multiple image\n| align  = right\n| footer = [[Morena Baccarin]], [[Rupert Friend]] and [[Morgan Saylor]] (left to right) portray Jessica Brody, Peter Quinn and Dana Brody, respectively.\n| image1 = Morena Baccarin by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| width1 = 144\n| image2 = Rupert Friend (cropped).jpg\n| width2 = 144\n| image3 = Morgan Saylor September 2015.jpg\n| width3 = 130\n}}\n* [[Claire Danes]] as [[Carrie Mathison]], a CIA intelligence officer assigned to the [[Counterterrorism Center]]\n* [[Damian Lewis]] as [[Nicholas Brody]], a [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine]]  Sergeant and a Marine Scout Sniper who was rescued by [[Delta Force]] after being held by [[al-Qaeda]] as a prisoner of war for eight years\n* [[Rupert Friend]] as Peter Quinn, a CIA black ops [[Special Activities Division|SOG/SAD]] operative\n* [[Morena Baccarin]] as Jessica Brody, Nicholas Brody's wife\n* [[Jackson Pace]] as Chris Brody, Nicholas Brody's son\n* [[Morgan Saylor]] as Dana Brody, Nicholas Brody's daughter\n* [[Sarita Choudhury]] as Mira Berenson, Saul's estranged wife\n* [[Tracy Letts]] as Senator Andrew Lockhart, the power hungry, authoritative and commanding Committee Chairman\n* [[F. Murray Abraham]] as Dar Adal, a retired black ops specialist\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]] as Saul Berenson, the Acting Director of the CIA and Carrie's old boss and mentor\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[James Rebhorn]] as Frank Mathison, Carrie's father\n* [[Tim Guinee]] as Scott Ryan, in charge of CIA special ops<ref>{{cite web|last=Guinee|first=Tim|title=Nice news today #Homeland is bringing me back.|url=https://twitter.com/TimGuinee/status/332296697986293761|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=May 8, 2013|accessdate=May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Sam Underwood]] as Leo Carras, a new friend of Dana's with a troubled past\n* Gary Wilmes as Dr. Troy Richardson, a psychiatrist helping Dana Brody cope with recent events\n* [[Nazanin Boniadi]] as Fara Sherazi, an intelligent, young and professional Persian analyst<ref name=E2>{{cite web|last=Bricker|first=Tierney|title=Spoiler Chat: Glee, The Vampire Diaries, The Office, Arrow and More!|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/416493/spoiler-chat-glee-the-vampire-diaries-the-office-arrow-and-more|work=[[E! Online]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|date=May 9, 2013|accessdate=May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Jason Butler Harner]] as Paul Franklin\n* [[David Marciano]] as Virgil Piotrowski, Carrie's contact<ref name = Virgil>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=David Marciano Departs \u2018Homeland\u2019 As Regular, Preps Cable Prison Drama|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/04/david-marciano-leaving-homeland-as-regular-castmember/|work=Deadline|date=April 11, 2013|accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Maury Sterling]] as Max Piotrowski, Virgil's brother\n* [[Shaun Toub]] as Majid Javadi, the Iranian Deputy Intelligence Chief who masterminded the Langley bombing<ref name=New2>{{cite web|last=O'Connell|first=Michael|title='Homeland' Casts Martin Donovan, 'Iron Man' Actor for Season 3|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-casts-martin-donovan-iron-585626|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 16, 2013|accessdate=July 17, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[William Abadie]] as Alan Bernard, an international journalist<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018General Hospital\u2019 Adds William deVry, William Abadie Joins \u2018Homeland\u2019|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/07/general-hospital-william-devry-homeland-william-abadie/|work=Deadline|date=July 10, 2013|accessdate=July 17, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[William Sadler (actor)|William Sadler]] as Mike Higgins, the White House Chief of Staff\n\n===Special guest===\n* [[Navid Negahban]] as Abu Nazir, a high-ranking member of al-Qaeda.\n\n===Guest===\n<!-- Only for actors credited as \"guest starring\" with an article on Wikipedia (except those appearing in two episodes or across seasons) -->\n* [[Amy Morton]] as Erin Kimball\n* [[Pedro Pascal]] as David Portillo\n* [[Joanna Merlin]] as Lois, Chris and Dana's grandmother\n* [[Amy Hargreaves]] as Maggie Mathison, Carrie's sister and a psychiatrist\n* [[David Aaron Baker]] as Dr. Harlan\n* [[Stephen Schnetzer]] as Dr. Maloney\n* [[Manny P\u00e9rez]] as El Ni\u00f1o\n* [[Martina Garc\u00eda]] as Esme\n* [[Erik Todd Dellums]] as Dr. Graham\n* Marcia DeBonis as Abby\n* Jennifer Marsala as Amanda Lambert\n* [[Diego Klattenhoff]] as Mike Faber, a U.S. Marine [[Major (United States)#U.S. Army, U.S. Air Force, and U.S. Marine Corps|Major]] (formerly [[Captain (United States)#U.S. Army, U.S. Air Force, and U.S. Marine Corps|Captain]]). He was Nicholas's best friend who, assuming Nicholas was dead, began an affair with his wife.\n* [[Martin Donovan]] as Leland Bennett, a partner in a Washington, D.C. law firm<ref name=New2/>\n* [[Stephanie J. Block]] as Patricia Cooper, a lawyer\n* [[Mary Apick]] as Fariba, Majid Javadi's former wife\n* Billy Smith as Special Agent Hall\n* [[Clark Johnson]] as Detective Johnson\n* [[Vincent Irizarry]] as Captain Lonza\n* [[Chance Kelly]] as Mitchell Clawson\n* [[Parviz Sayyad]] as Mr. Sherazi\n* [[Donnie Keshawarz]] as Hafez Azizi\n* Jared Ward as Yousef Turani\n* Walid Amini as Josh Modarres\n* Jaylen Moore as Eric Baraz\n* [[Chris Chalk]] as Tom Walker, a U.S. Marine who was captured along with Brody\n* [[David Diaan]] as Masud Sharazi\n* Houshang Touzie as General Danesh Akbari, the Iranian Intelligence Chief\n\n==Episodes==\n{{See also|List of Homeland episodes}}\n<onlyinclude>{{Episode table |background=#FFC50A |overall=5 |season=5 |title=22 |director=13 |writer=27 |airdate=12 |prodcode=7 |viewers=9 |country=US |episodes =\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=25\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title=[[Tin Man Is Down]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Lesli Linka Glatter]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Alex Gansa]] & [[Barbara Hall (TV producer)|Barbara Hall]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|9|29}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH01\n |Viewers=1.88<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/10/01/sunday-cable-ratingsbreaking-bad-wins-big-talking-bad-homeland-boardwalk-empiremasters-of-sex-more/205986/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'Breaking Bad' Wins Big, 'Talking Bad', 'Homeland', 'Boardwalk Empire','Masters of Sex' & More |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Sara |last=Bibel |date=October 1, 2013 |accessdate=October 1, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024033044/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/10/01/sunday-cable-ratingsbreaking-bad-wins-big-talking-bad-homeland-boardwalk-empiremasters-of-sex-more/205986/ |archivedate=October 24, 2013 }}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Carrie and Saul are both called to testify before Congress. Dana is released from the hospital following her suicide attempt. The CIA coordinates six simultaneous attacks across the world to kill the people responsible for planning the CIA bombing.\n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=26\n |EpisodeNumber2=2\n |Title=[[Uh... Oh... Ah...]]\n |DirectedBy=Lesli Linka Glatter\n |WrittenBy=[[Chip Johannessen]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|10|6}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH02\n |Viewers=1.83<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/10/08/sunday-cable-ratings-keeping-up-with-the-kardashians-thursday-night-fo