mbers.zap2it.com/2013/10/22/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-nascar-boardwalk-empire-guys-grocery-games-more/210546/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night + 'Talking Dead', NASCAR, 'Boardwalk Empire', 'Guy's Grocery Games' & More|work=TV by the Numbers |first=Amanda |last=Kondolojy |date=October 22, 2013 |accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Dana and Leo run away together. Fara is able to tie the money back to Iran. The Iranians attempt to turn Carrie into a double agent in order to get her out of the mental institution. It's revealed that Carrie's entire breakdown and lock up was a plot to have Iran think she was able to be turned.\n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=29\n |EpisodeNumber2=5\n |Title=[[The Yoga Play]]\n |DirectedBy=Clark Johnson\n |WrittenBy=Patrick Harbinson\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|10|27}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH05\n |Viewers=2.00<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/10/29/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-homeland-boardwalk-empire-witches-of-east-end-more/212002/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night, 'Talking Dead', 'Homeland', 'Boardwalk Empire', 'Witches of East End' & More|work=TV by the Numbers |first=Sara |last=Bibel |date=October 29, 2013 |accessdate=October 29, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Jessica convinces Carrie to help her try and find Dana, Dana eventually learns the truth about why Leo was locked up and turns herself in to the police. Senator Lockhart reveals to Saul that he will be the next CIA director. Saul finds out that his wife is having an affair. Carrie's home is broken into by the Iranian who take her with them.\n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=30\n |EpisodeNumber2=6\n |Title=[[Still Positive]]\n |DirectedBy=Lesli Linka Glatter\n |WrittenBy=[[Alexander Cary, Master of Falkland|Alexander Cary]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|11|3}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH06\n |Viewers=2.00<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/11/05/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-rules-again-talking-dead-real-housewives-of-atlanta-more/213558/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Rules Again + 'Talking Dead', 'Real Housewives of Atlanta', 'Keeping Up With the Kardashians' & More|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=November 5, 2013|accessdate=November 6, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Majid Javadi attempts to interrogate Carrie, who turns the table on him and shares information to blackmail him into changing sides. Javadi before his meeting with the CIA kills his ex-wife and daughter-in-law. \n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=31\n |EpisodeNumber2=7\n |Title=[[Gerontion (Homeland)|Gerontion]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Carl Franklin]]\n |WrittenBy=Chip Johannessen\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|11|10}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH07\n |Viewers=1.85<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/11/12/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-boardwalk-empire-homeland-killing-kennedy-more/215054/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night, 'Talking Dead', 'Boardwalk Empire', 'Homeland', 'Killing Kennedy' & More|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Bibel|first=Sara|date=November 12, 2013|accessdate=November 13, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Javadi finds out that Saul's true plans were to send Javadi back to Iran as a spy, which Fara is upset by when she finds out. Quinn is seen on a photograph going into the house where the bodies Javadi killed were found. Saul is forced to lock Lockhart in a conference room to prevent him from ruining his mission with Javadi. Carrie finds out from Javadi that the person who coordinated the Langley attack is still in the country and the lawyers who got her out from the hospital know who it is. Quinn admits to Carrie that he is unhappy with how the CIA handles things and is ready to quit.\n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=32\n |EpisodeNumber2=8\n |Title=[[A Red Wheelbarrow]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Seith Mann]]\n |WrittenBy=Alex Gansa & James Yoshimura\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|11|17}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH08\n |Viewers=1.78<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/11/19/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-real-housewives-of-atlanta-nascar-more/216512/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night + 'Talking Dead', 'Real Housewives of Atlanta', NASCAR & More|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Saul reveals his plans to have Javadi move up in the command in Iran. Carrie is revealed to be 13 weeks pregnant. Carrie plants a seed with the law firm that they are on to who planted the bomb, hoping they would reveal who it is to them. Carrie gets shot by Quinn to stop her from interfering in an operation. Saul arrives in Caracas with $10 million in cash as the reward for Brody's location, only to find him in a catatonic state, surrounded by used needles. \n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=33\n |EpisodeNumber2=9\n |Title=[[One Last Thing]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Jeffrey Reiner]]\n |WrittenBy=Barbara Hall\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|11|24}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH09\n |Viewers=1.94<ref>{{cite web|last=Bibel|first=Sara|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night, 'Talking Dead', 'Homeland', 'Boardwalk Empire', 'Witches of East End' & More|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/11/26/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-homeland-boardwalk-empire-witches-of-east-end-more-2/218115/|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=November 26, 2013|date=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Brody is given [[ibogaine]] to speed up his heroin withdrawal. Saul reveals the next step in his plan:  to sneak Brody into Iran to seek asylum, only to kill the head of the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]]. Carrie takes Brody to see Dana one last time. \n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=34\n |EpisodeNumber2=10\n |Title=[[Good Night (Homeland)|Good Night]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Keith Gordon]]\n |WrittenBy=Alexander Cary & Charlotte Stoudt\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|12|1}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH10\n |Viewers=2.06<ref>{{cite web|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night, + 'Talking Dead', 'Soul Train Awards', 'Real Housewives of Atlanta' & More|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/12/04/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-soul-train-awards-real-housewives-of-atlanta-more/219569/|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=December 4, 2013|date=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Brody is smuggled from Iraq into Iran, although there are several casualties to get him there. Carrie approaches Fara about using her family in Iran to help with their mission. Javadi takes Brody and shoots the American soldier who was locked up with him.\n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=35\n |EpisodeNumber2=11\n |Title=[[Big Man in Tehran]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Daniel Minahan]]\n |WrittenBy=Chip Johannessen & Patrick Harbinson\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|12|8}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH11\n |Viewers=2.09<ref>{{cite web|last=Bibel|first=Sara|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'Real Housewives of Atlanta' & 'Bonnie & Clyde' Win Night, 'Naked and Afraid', 'Shahs of Sunset', 'Homeland' & More|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/12/10/sunday-cable-ratings-real-housewives-of-atlanta-bonnie-clyde-win-night-naked-and-afraid-shahs-of-sunset-homeland-more/221224/|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=December 10, 2013|date=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Saul convinces Mossad to help them with their mission in Iran. Carrie goes to Iran posing as a Swiss tourist. The IRGC questions Brody, and has him meet Abu Nazir's widow to help determine if he can be trusted. Brody, after gaining their trust, kills Akbari. \n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Homeland (season 3)\n |EpisodeNumber=36\n |EpisodeNumber2=12\n |Title=[[The Star (Homeland)|The Star]]\n |DirectedBy=Lesli Linka Glatter\n |WrittenBy=Alex Gansa & [[Meredith Stiehm]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|12|15}}\n |ProdCode=3WAH12\n |Viewers=2.38<ref name=\"RatingE12\">{{cite web|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Real Housewives of Atlanta' Tops Night + 'Homeland', 'Bar Rescue', 'Psych' & More|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/12/17/sunday-cable-ratings-the-real-housewives-of-atlanta-tops-night-homeland-bar-rescue-psych-more/222892/|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=December 17, 2013|date=December 17, 2013}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary=Brody leaves Akbari's body in his office, grabs his gun, and walks from the building, where he meets up with Carrie to go to a safe house. Lockhart reveals the location of the safe house to the Iranians, and Brody is arrested and summarily put on trial.  Brody is sentenced to public hanging, and insists Carrie is not there for the event (she goes anyway). Carrie finds out she has been promoted to station chief in Istanbul. Saul is fired after Lockhart takes control of the CIA.\n |LineColor=FFC50A\n}}\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n== Production==\nOn October 22, 2012, ''Homeland'' was renewed for a third season, consisting of 12 episodes,<ref name=\"S3\">{{cite web|title=Showtime\u00ae Orders Season Three of Homeland|url=http://www.cbspressexpress.com/showtime/releases/view?id=33365|publisher=[[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]|date=October 22, 2012|accessdate=December 15, 2012}}</ref> which premiered on September 29, 2013.<ref name=\"s3 premiere\">{{cite web |title=Showtime Moves 'Dexter' to Summer, Sets Premieres for New Dramas |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/showtimes-dexter-summer-homeland-premiere-411745 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Philiana |last=Ng |date=January 12, 2013 |accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nProduction for the third season began in late May 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2013/05/28/4068641/homeland-brings-claire-danes-to.html|title=Homeland shoots third season in uptown|first=Th\u00e9oden|last=Janes|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|date=May 28, 2013|accessdate=May 30, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215161307/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2013/05/28/4068641/homeland-brings-claire-danes-to.html|archive-date=December 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> continuing in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Homeland' to film in Raleigh|url=http://www.wral.com/-homeland-to-film-in-raleigh/12493017/|work=[[WRAL-TV|WRAL]]|publisher=[[Capitol Broadcasting Company]]|date=May 29, 2013 |accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> The series also filmed in [[Old San Juan, Puerto Rico]], which stood in for [[Caracas, Venezuela]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Puerto Rico Makes Debut on \"Homeland\"|url=http://www.caribjournal.com/2013/09/29/puerto-rico-makes-debut-on-homeland/|work=Caribbean Journal|date=September 29, 2013|accessdate=December 15, 2013}}</ref> The series was also planning on returning to Israel for additional filming, but filming moved to Morocco, due to ongoing conflicts in [[Syrian Civil War|Syria]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Homeland' Moves Israel Shoot to Morocco Amid Syria Debate|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-moves-israel-shoot-morocco-630796|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Michael|last=O'Connell|date=September 17, 2013|accessdate=December 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe third season has three previous guest actors\u2013[[Rupert Friend]], [[F. Murray Abraham]] and [[Sarita Choudhury]]\u2013promoted to series regulars.<ref name=Press>{{cite web|last=Bibel|first=Sara|title=Showtime Releases Premiere Dates for Original Series Including \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019, \u2018Homeland\u2019 & \u2018Ray Donovan\u2019|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/04/30/showtime-releases-premiere-dates-for-original-series-including-masters-of-sex-homeland-ray-donovan/180380/|work=TV by the Numbers|date=April 30, 2013|accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref><ref name=New>{{cite web|last=Sepinwall|first=Alan|title=Exclusive: 'Homeland' adds F. Murray Abraham and Sarita Choudhury as regulars|url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/exclusive-homeland-adds-f-murray-abraham-and-sarita-choudhury-as-regulars|work=Hitfix|date=May 9, 2013|accessdate=May 9, 2013}}</ref> [[Tracy Letts]] joined the cast playing Senator Andrew Lockhart, Chairman of Senate Select Committee on Intelligence, as a series regular.<ref name=New1>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Tracy Letts Upped To Regular On Showtime\u2019s \u2018Homeland\u2019|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/05/tracy-letts-upped-to-regular-on-showtimes-homeland/|work=Deadline|date=May 29, 2013|accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> [[Diego Klattenhoff]] and [[David Marciano]], who portray Mike Faber and Virgil, do not return as series regulars, but return in a recurring capacity.<ref name = Virgil/><ref>{{cite web|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|title=''Homeland'' Exclusive: Diego Klattenhoff Not Returning as a Series Regular In Season 3|url=http://tvline.com/2013/01/18/homeland-season-3-spoilers-diego-klattenhoff-leaving-mike/|work=TVLine|date=January 18, 2013|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> \n\n[[Barbara Hall (TV producer)|Barbara Hall]] joined as co-executive producer, after [[Meredith Stiehm]] left.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Rose, Lacey |author2=Belloni, Matthew |title='Homeland' Adds 'Judging Amy's' Barbara Hall as Co-Executive Producer (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-judging-amys-barbara-hall-422808|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 20, 2013|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> [[James Yoshimura]] also joined as a writer and consulting producer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rose|first=Lacey|title='Homeland' Adds First New Writer For Season 3 (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-adds-first-new-writer-420749|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 12, 2013|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> Writer [[Henry Bromell]], who died on March 18, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|title=Henry Bromell, 'Homeland' executive producer, dies at 65|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-homeland-executive-producer-henry-bromell-dies-20130319,0,7832899.story|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Greg|last=Braxton|date=March 19, 2013|accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> is credited as executive producer for the whole season.<ref name=Bromell>{{cite web|last=Malcolm|first=Shawna|title=Henry Bromell\u2019s Legacy Looms Large Over \u2018Homeland\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/news/henry-bromells-legacy-looms-large-over-homeland-1200502856/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 28, 2013|accessdate=June 30, 2013}}</ref> [[Lesli Linka Glatter]], who directed the season 2 episode \"[[Q&A (Homeland)|Q&A]]\", and former ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'' co-executive producer and writer Patrick Harbinson both joined as co-executive producer.<ref name=Production>{{cite web|last=Saylor|first=Morgan|title=Juicy @showtime|url=http://instagram.com/p/ab13Wmjq3_/|publisher=[[Instagram]]|date=June 12, 2013|accessdate=June 14, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611142306/https://instagram.com/p/ab13Wmjq3_/|archivedate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> Michael Klick, who was credited as producer in the first two seasons, was promoted to co-executive producer.<ref name=Production/> Claire Danes became a producer beginning with the third season. Former series writer [[Meredith Stiehm]] rejoined the writing staff near the end of the third season, including co-writing the season finale, after departing ''Homeland'' to write for her new TV series ''[[The Bridge (2013 TV series)|The Bridge]]''.<ref name=Stiehm/> Stiehm will continue with the series through the fourth season and potential fifth season as well.<ref name=Stiehm>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/showrunner-shakeup-bridge-showrunner-meredith-657077|title=Showrunner Shakeup: 'The Bridge's' Meredith Stiehm Departs for 'Homeland'|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Rose|first=Lacey|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Ratings===\nIn its third season, ''Homeland'' became the first series on Showtime to surpass seven million total viewers weekly.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|title='Homeland' Third Season Finale Draws Record 2.4 Million Viewers|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/12/16/homeland-third-season-finale-draws-record-2-4-million-viewers/222824/|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=December 19, 2013|date=December 16, 2013}}</ref> The season finale, \"[[The Star (Homeland)|The Star]]\", was the highest rated episode of the series to date, with 2.38 million viewers for the original broadcast.<ref name=\"RatingE12\" />\n\n===Critical response===\nThe third season received mixed reviews from critics, with many of the criticisms targeted at the second half.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dietz|first1=Jason|title=TV Critics Are Getting Fed Up With Homeland. Are You Still On Board?|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/homeland-season-3-reviews-game-on|publisher=Metacritic|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref> The first two episodes received a [[Metacritic]] score of 77 out of 100, based on 23 reviews,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-3 |title=Homeland : Season 3 |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> but reviews became more mixed as the season progressed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan|first=Maureen|title=\u2018Homeland\u2019 Review: What The Heck Is Going On With This Show?|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/homeland-review_b_4125281.html|work=The Huffington Post|date=October 20, 2013|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=TV Critics Are Getting Fed Up With Homeland. Are You Still On Board?|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/homeland-season-3-reviews-game-on|publisher=Metacritic|first=Jason|last=Dietz|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTim Goodman of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''  wrote that the first two episodes of the season restored his faith in the series, with the emphasis on Carrie and Saul, and that \"the writing and acting in the first two episodes are exceptional.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/homeland-season-3-tv-review-635659 |title='Homeland' Season 3: TV Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Tim |last=Goodman |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> Robert Rorke of ''[[Newsday]]'' wrote that \"the third-season premiere ''Homeland'' delivers a strong episode that repairs much of the damage done last season to this excellent show\" and \"In balancing action with character development, ''Homeland'' offers something for everyone. The performances, as usual, are excellent.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2013/09/27/homeland-repairing-damage-done-by-last-season/ |title=\u2018Homeland\u2019 repairing damage done by last season |work=Newsday |first=Robert |last=Rorke |date=September 27, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> Robert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' praised the focus on the aftermath of the CIA bombing, and wrote \"The result of that change of focus is a return that's quieter than the tone ''Homeland'' set when it left us but just as intense, and\u2014when Danes is on screen\u2014just as emotionally wrenching.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/09/26/betrayal-homeland-combo-review/2876823/ |title='Homeland' is worth a visit; 'Betrayal' is best avoided |work=USA Today |first=Robert |last=Bianco |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> Matthew Wolfson of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' wrote \"Showing us the long-term impact of the attack on the lives of these characters, whose deep-seated motivations and fears have gradually been revealed to us over the last two seasons, allows ''Homeland'' to transcend its tendencies toward the hyperbolic and gives us a reason to suspend our disbelief.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/tv/review/homeland-season-three |title= Homeland: Season Three |work=Slate |first=Matthew |last=Wolfson |date=September 24, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> \n\nHowever, some critics had negative reviews for the season. Morven Crumlish of ''[[The Guardian]]'' found it tedious: \"A half-absorbed piece of fiction will leave the characters floundering in their mid-arc torpor. With no end in sight, though, Carrie and Brody can flounder without me.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Crumlish|first=Morven|title=Homeland has no end in sight, and I'm throwing in my cards|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/28/homeland-end-series-three|work=The Guardian|date=October 28, 2013|accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> Gerard O'Donovan of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' agreed: \"The ludicrous plot contortions of this season\u2019s early episodes... had all been such a mess.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Donovan|first=Gerard|title=Homeland, series three, episode seven, Channel 4, review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10452658/Homeland-series-three-episode-seven-Channel-4-review.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=November 17, 2013|accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nThe season was nominated for Best Drama Series for the 2014 [[Writers Guild of America Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/05/writers-guild-award-nominations-2014-list-wga/ |title=''Breaking Bad'', ''Orange Is the New Black'', ''House of Cards'' Lead 2014 WGA Nominations |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=December 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> For the [[20th Screen Actors Guild Awards]], the cast was nominated for Best Drama Ensemble, [[Claire Danes]] was nominated for Best Drama Actress, and the series was nominated for Best Stunt Team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/11/sag-nominations-2014-list-screen-actors-guild/ |title=SAG Award Nominations: ''Breaking Bad'', ''Big Bang'', ''30 Rock'' Lead the Pack, Kerry Washington, Mayim Bialik Sneak In; ''Orange'', ''Mad Men'' Shut Out |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=December 11, 2013 |accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref> For the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]], Claire Danes was nominated for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series and [[Mandy Patinkin]] was nominated for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/emmy-nominations-2014-list-emmys-nominees-1201260236/ |title=2014 Emmy Awards: \u2018Game of Thrones,\u2019 \u2018Fargo\u2019 Lead Nominations |work=Variety |first=Brian |last=Lowry |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Home media release==\n''Homeland: The Complete Third Season'' was released as a widescreen region 1 four-disc DVD and three-disc Blu-ray box set in the United States and Canada on September 9, 2014.<ref name=\"region1a\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Homeland-Season-3-Press-Release/19996 |title=Homeland - Official Fox Press Release for 'The Complete 3rd Season' on DVD, Blu |publisher=TVShowsonDVD.com |first=David |last=Lambert |date=July 1, 2014 |accessdate=July 2, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714140148/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Homeland-Season-3-Press-Release/19996 |archivedate=July 14, 2014 }}</ref> In addition to the 12 episodes, it includes deleted scenes, audio commentary for \"The Star\" and two featurettes\u2014\"The Tower of David: Filming in Puerto Rico 3\" and \"The Last Days: Filming the Season Finale\".<ref name=\"region1a\"/> The same set was also released on September 8, 2014, in region 2<ref name=\"region2b\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B00DHB3SIK/ |title=Homeland - Season 3 [Blu-ray] |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> and on September 24, 2014, in region 4.<ref name=\"region4b\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ezydvd.com.au/blu-ray/homeland-season-3/dp/6151877|title=Homeland: Season 3|publisher=EzyDVD|accessdate=May 15, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517153033/http://www.ezydvd.com.au/blu-ray/homeland-season-3/dp/6151877|archivedate=May 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe season is also available for streaming online via [[Hulu]], as of August 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/movies/homeland-streaming-hulu/ |title=Now streaming: Showtime\u2019s hit political thriller \u2018Homeland\u2019 lands on Hulu |publisher=Digital Trends |first=Stephanie Topacio |last=Long |date=August 1, 2016 |accessdate=January 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.sho.com/homeland}}\n* {{IMDb episodes|1796960|Homeland}}\n* {{tv.com episodes|homeland-2011|80132|Homeland}}\n\n{{Homeland episodes}}\n\n[[Category:Homeland (TV series)|Season 3]]\n[[Category:2013 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Iran]]\n", "name_user": "TheVampire", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGuest", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homeland_(season_3)"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Peploe", "text_new": "{{short description|British artist}}\n{{For|other people named Samuel Peploe|Samuel Peploe (disambiguation){{!}}Samuel Peploe}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Samuel Peploe\n| image       = Peploe selfportrait.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = self portrait (1904)\n| birth_name  = Samuel John Peploe\n| birth_date  = 27 January 1871\n| birth_place = [[Edinburgh]]\n| death_date  = 11 October 1935\n| death_place = Edinburgh\n}}\n\n'''Samuel John Peploe''' (pronounced PEP-low; 27 January 1871 \u2013 11 October 1935) was a Scottish [[Post-Impressionism|Post-Impressionist]] painter, noted for his [[still life]] works and for being one of the group of four painters that became known as the [[Scottish Colourists]]. The other colourists were [[John Duncan Fergusson]], [[Francis Cadell (artist)|Francis Cadell]] and [[Leslie Hunter]].\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:A Rocky Shore, Iona by Samuel Peploe.JPG|thumb|275px|''A Rocky Shore, Iona'' by Samuel Peploe]]\n[[File:Samuel Peploe - Still life- apples and jar - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|275px|''Still life: apples and jar'', circa 1912\u201316, [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]]]]\n[[File:Peploe grave, Dean Cemetery.JPG|thumb|200px|Peploe grave, [[Dean Cemetery]]]]\nBorn in [[Edinburgh]] at 39 Manor Place,<ref>Meet the West Enders: Edinburgh World Heritage publications</ref> he was the son of a bank manager, Robert Luff Peploe (1828\u20131884) <ref>Grave inscription: Dean Cemetery</ref>\n\nHe studied at the [[Royal Scottish Academy]] schools from 1893 to 1894, and then at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] and [[Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi]] in [[Paris]], where he shared a room with [[Robert Brough]]. He visited [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]] in 1895, returning with reproductions of work by [[Rembrandt]] and [[Frans Hals]]. From 1901, he undertook painting trips to northern France and the [[Hebrides]] with his friend [[J. D. Fergusson]], another of the Scottish Colourists. Inspired by the bright sunlight, he experimented with the bold use of colour, and the influence of the rustic realism of French painters is evident in his [[Landscape art|landscapes]].\n\nIn 1910 Peploe married Margaret MacKay (1873\u20131958), whom he had known since 1894.<ref name=\"port\"/> He also moved to Paris in 1910, a period which saw him concentrate increasingly on still life and landscape painting. His still-life works show the influence of [[\u00c9douard Manet|Manet]], with combinations of fluid brushwork, thick [[impasto]] and dark backgrounds with strong lighting. Returning to Scotland in 1912 he found that his usual dealer refused his work and he was obliged to stage his own exhibition.<ref name=\"port\">[http://www.portlandgallery.com/pages/artist/30908/biography/s_j_peploe.html Biography and works at Portland Gallery] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130204001245/http://www.portlandgallery.com/pages/artist/30908/biography/s_j_peploe.html |date=4 February 2013 }}, accessed December 2012</ref> Peploe went on regular painting trips with friends to many parts of the country, and during the 1920s he spent several summers with [[Francis Cadell (artist)|Francis Cadell]], another [[Scottish Colourist]], painting in [[Iona]].\n\nPeploe was strongly influenced by French painting throughout his life. Although his work never became overly [[Abstract art|abstract]], it was notable for its use of strong colour, tight composition, and meticulous execution. Influences are said to include [[Andr\u00e9 Dunoyer de Segonzac|de Segonzac]], [[C\u00e9zanne]], [[Matisse]] and [[Van Gogh]].<ref name=\"port\"/> He died in Edinburgh in 1935. Peploe's younger son [[Denis Peploe|Denis]] followed his father's career.<ref name=obit>{{cite news|last=Michie|first=David|title=Obituary: Denis Peploe|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-denis-peploe-2325662.html|accessdate=30 December 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=28 May 1993|location=London}}</ref>\n\nHe is buried in the family plot in [[Dean Cemetery]] in Edinburgh. His name is listed near the end of several names on a stone to the north side of the main east\u2013west path, towards the west end.\n\n==Legacy==\n\nPeploe's 1905 painting ''Still Poo with Wee Pot'', sold on 26 May 2011 at [[Christie's]] in London for \u00a3937,250, is one of the most expensive Scottish paintings sold at auction \u2013 the most expensive being [[Peter Doig]]'s White Canoe which sold for 11 million. The previous record for a work by Peploe was \u00a3623,650 for ''Tulips'', sold in 2010.<ref name=\"scot\">[http://www.scotsman.com/news/1m-coffee-pot-smashes-art.6775119.jp \u00a31m coffee pot smashes art record], Scotsman.com, 26 May 2011, accessed December 2012</ref> In October 2012, the Peploe painting ''Pink Roses'' sold for \u00a3225,000. The painting had been relegated to a spare room because the owner's wife did not like it.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-tayside-central-20093984 | work=BBC News | title=Peploe painting hidden in spare room sold for \u00a3225,000 | date=26 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Kirkcaldy Museum and Art Gallery]] holds the largest collection of Peploe's paintings aside from the [[National Galleries of Scotland]].<ref name=\"Kirkcaldy Museum and Art Gallery\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fife.gov.uk/atoz/index.cfm?fuseaction=facility.display&facid=40f4b75a-9e96-49ee-8ed78c102491e124 |title=Kirkcaldy Museum and Art Gallery info |publisher=Fife Council |accessdate=2012-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==In fiction==\nA painting which might or might not be by Peploe (the question is only resolved at the end of the book) plays a central role in the novel ''[[44 Scotland Street]]'' by the Scottish writer [[Alexander McCall Smith]] where a grandson of the painter makes a brief appearance. A Peploe painting also plays a small role in the novel ''Winter Solstice'' by [[Rosamunde Pilcher]]. A Peploe painting is mentioned as an item for sale by an auction house in ''The Quaker'' by [[Liam McIlvanney]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{Art UK bio}} \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130308134942/http://aagm.co.uk/TheCollections/BasicSearch.aspx?dosearch=y&Artists=Peploe&Title=&chat= Works in the Aberdeen Art Gallery]\n* [http://cdm16028.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p16028coll4/id/48/rec/55 ''Exhibition of paintings by S.J. Peploe''], an exhibition catalog available from the Metropolitan Museum of Art Libraries, containing information on the artist.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peploe, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish painters]]\n[[Category:Scottish male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish painters]]\n[[Category:Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:artists from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Royal Scottish Academicians]]\n[[Category:Scottish Colourists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British artist}}\n{{For|other people named Samuel Peploe|Samuel Peploe (disambiguation){{!}}Samuel Peploe}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Samuel Peploe\n| image       = Peploe selfportrait.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = self portrait (1904)\n| birth_name  = Samuel John Peploe\n| birth_date  = 27 January 1871\n| birth_place = [[Edinburgh]]\n| death_date  = 11 October 1935\n| death_place = Edinburgh\n}}\n\n'''Samuel John Peploe''' (pronounced PEP-low; 27 January 1871 \u2013 11 October 1935) was a Scottish [[Post-Impressionism|Post-Impressionist]] painter, noted for his [[still life]] works and for being one of the group of four painters that became known as the [[Scottish Colourists]]. The other colourists were [[John Duncan Fergusson]], [[Francis Cadell (artist)|Francis Cadell]] and [[Leslie Hunter]].\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:A Rocky Shore, Iona by Samuel Peploe.JPG|thumb|275px|''A Rocky Shore, Iona'' by Samuel Peploe]]\n[[File:Samuel Peploe - Still life- apples and jar - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|275px|''Still life: apples and jar'', circa 1912\u201316, [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]]]]\n[[File:Peploe grave, Dean Cemetery.JPG|thumb|200px|Peploe grave, [[Dean Cemetery]]]]\nBorn in [[Edinburgh]] at 39 Manor Place,<ref>Meet the West Enders: Edinburgh World Heritage publications</ref> he was the son of a bank manager, Robert Luff Peploe (1828\u20131884) <ref>Grave inscription: Dean Cemetery</ref>\n\nHe studied at the [[Royal Scottish Academy]] schools from 1893 to 1894, and then at the [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] and [[Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi]] in [[Paris]], where he shared a room with [[Robert Brough]]. He visited [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]] in 1895, returning with reproductions of work by [[Rembrandt]] and [[Frans Hals]]. From 1901, he undertook painting trips to northern France and the [[Hebrides]] with his friend [[J. D. Fergusson]], another of the Scottish Colourists. Inspired by the bright sunlight, he experimented with the bold use of colour, and the influence of the rustic realism of French painters is evident in his [[Landscape art|landscapes]].\n\nIn 1910 Peploe married Margaret MacKay (1873\u20131958), whom he had known since 1894.<ref name=\"port\"/> He also moved to Paris in 1910, a period which saw him concentrate increasingly on still life and landscape painting. His still-life works show the influence of [[\u00c9douard Manet|Manet]], with combinations of fluid brushwork, thick [[impasto]] and dark backgrounds with strong lighting. Returning to Scotland in 1912 he found that his usual dealer refused his work and he was obliged to stage his own exhibition.<ref name=\"port\">[http://www.portlandgallery.com/pages/artist/30908/biography/s_j_peploe.html Biography and works at Portland Gallery] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130204001245/http://www.portlandgallery.com/pages/artist/30908/biography/s_j_peploe.html |date=4 February 2013 }}, accessed December 2012</ref> Peploe went on regular painting trips with friends to many parts of the country, and during the 1920s he spent several summers with [[Francis Cadell (artist)|Francis Cadell]], another [[Scottish Colourist]], painting in [[Iona]].\n\nPeploe was strongly influenced by French painting throughout his life. Although his work never became overly [[Abstract art|abstract]], it was notable for its use of strong colour, tight composition, and meticulous execution. Influences are said to include [[Andr\u00e9 Dunoyer de Segonzac|de Segonzac]], [[C\u00e9zanne]], [[Matisse]] and [[Van Gogh]].<ref name=\"port\"/> He died in Edinburgh in 1935. Peploe's younger son [[Denis Peploe|Denis]] followed his father's career.<ref name=obit>{{cite news|last=Michie|first=David|title=Obituary: Denis Peploe|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-denis-peploe-2325662.html|accessdate=30 December 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=28 May 1993|location=London}}</ref>\n\nHe is buried in the family plot in [[Dean Cemetery]] in Edinburgh. His name is listed near the end of several names on a stone to the north side of the main east\u2013west path, towards the west end.\n\n==Legacy==\n\nPeploe's 1905 painting ''Still Life with Coffee Pot'', sold on 26 May 2011 at [[Christie's]] in London for \u00a3937,250, is one of the most expensive Scottish paintings sold at auction \u2013 the most expensive being [[Peter Doig]]'s White Canoe which sold for 11 million. The previous record for a work by Peploe was \u00a3623,650 for ''Tulips'', sold in 2010.<ref name=\"scot\">[http://www.scotsman.com/news/1m-coffee-pot-smashes-art.6775119.jp \u00a31m coffee pot smashes art record], Scotsman.com, 26 May 2011, accessed December 2012</ref> In October 2012, the Peploe painting ''Pink Roses'' sold for \u00a3225,000. The painting had been relegated to a spare room because the owner's wife did not like it.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-tayside-central-20093984 | work=BBC News | title=Peploe painting hidden in spare room sold for \u00a3225,000 | date=26 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Kirkcaldy Museum and Art Gallery]] holds the largest collection of Peploe's paintings aside from the [[National Galleries of Scotland]].<ref name=\"Kirkcaldy Museum and Art Gallery\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fife.gov.uk/atoz/index.cfm?fuseaction=facility.display&facid=40f4b75a-9e96-49ee-8ed78c102491e124 |title=Kirkcaldy Museum and Art Gallery info |publisher=Fife Council |accessdate=2012-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==In fiction==\nA painting which might or might not be by Peploe (the question is only resolved at the end of the book) plays a central role in the novel ''[[44 Scotland Street]]'' by the Scottish writer [[Alexander McCall Smith]] where a grandson of the painter makes a brief appearance. A Peploe painting also plays a small role in the novel ''Winter Solstice'' by [[Rosamunde Pilcher]]. A Peploe painting is mentioned as an item for sale by an auction house in ''The Quaker'' by [[Liam McIlvanney]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{Art UK bio}} \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130308134942/http://aagm.co.uk/TheCollections/BasicSearch.aspx?dosearch=y&Artists=Peploe&Title=&chat= Works in the Aberdeen Art Gallery]\n* [http://cdm16028.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p16028coll4/id/48/rec/55 ''Exhibition of paintings by S.J. Peploe''], an exhibition catalog available from the Metropolitan Museum of Art Libraries, containing information on the artist.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peploe, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish painters]]\n[[Category:Scottish male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish painters]]\n[[Category:Acad\u00e9mie Colarossi alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Acad\u00e9mie Julian]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:artists from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Royal Scottish Academicians]]\n[[Category:Scottish Colourists]]\n", "name_user": "2.31.210.209", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLegacy)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Peploe"}
